 Given the observations of the system state, one can estimate the transition probabilities and the initial probabilities using [53], [54]: 

•\$N_{i,j}\equiv{}\$ number of observation pairs, \$X_t\$ & \$X_{t+1}\$, with \$X_t\$ in state \$i\$, and \$X_{t+1}\$ in state \$j\$;
•\$N_{i.}\equiv{}\$ number of observation pairs, \$X_t\$ & \$X_{t+1}\$, with \$X_t\$ in state \$i\$ and \$X_{t+1}\$ in any one of the states \$1, \ldots, s\$;
•\$N_i\equiv{}\$ number of \$X_t\$'s in state \$i\$;
•\$N\equiv{}\$ total number of observations.

